<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="437" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1503,2034]" pageId="16" pageNumber="437">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1575,1601]" pageId="16" pageNumber="437">Description</emphasis>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[405,503,1575,1601]" pageId="16" pageNumber="437">holotype</typeStatus>
is an encrusting colony featuring a thin, irregular spreading membrane (&lt;
<quantity box="[1360,1428,1576,1602]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="437" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
) growing on dead coral skeleton and measuring approximately 10 x 
<quantity box="[939,1021,1612,1638]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="16" pageNumber="437" unit="mm" value="18.0">18 mm</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[1039,1147,1611,1638]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1214,1238]" captionTargetBox="[157,1430,309,1191]" captionTargetId="figure-65@17.[157,1430,309,1191]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 16. Quattuoria pallida gen. nov. sp. nov. Holotype (SMNHTAU_Co_36071): (A) Encrusting colony attached to a calcareous fragment. (B) Magnified portion of holotype showing expanded polyps." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5912769" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5912769/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="437">Fig. 16A</figureCitation>
). Some smaller detached fragments of a few polyps each are also included in the 
<typeStatus box="[761,863,1647,1673]" pageId="16" pageNumber="437">holotype</typeStatus>
.All polyps are fully expanded (
<figureCitation box="[1212,1313,1647,1674]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1214,1238]" captionTargetBox="[157,1430,309,1191]" captionTargetId="figure-65@17.[157,1430,309,1191]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 16. Quattuoria pallida gen. nov. sp. nov. Holotype (SMNHTAU_Co_36071): (A) Encrusting colony attached to a calcareous fragment. (B) Magnified portion of holotype showing expanded polyps." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5912769" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5912769/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="437">Fig. 16B</figureCitation>
): the polyp body is 
<quantity box="[242,337,1683,1710]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="437" unit="mm" value="4.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="4.0">4–5 mm</quantity>
long and the tentacles up to 
<quantity box="[666,763,1684,1710]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="437" unit="mm" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3–4 mm</quantity>
. When the tentacles are viewed from the aboral side 18–25 pinnules can be counted on either margin of the tentacle, with almost no space between adjacent ones. When viewed from the oral side, numerous densely placed pinnules occupy almost the entire oral side of the tentacle, notably not arranged in rows.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1503,2034]" pageId="16" pageNumber="437">
The sclerites are spheroid or ellipsoid platelets (
<figureCitation box="[772,878,1827,1854]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1106,1130]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1082]" captionTargetId="figure-23@18.[151,1436,181,1082]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 17. Scanning electron micrographs of sclerites of Quattuoria pallida gen. nov. sp. nov. Holotype (SMNHTAU_Co_ 36071): (A) Ellipsoid platelets, a few with surface irregularity. (B) Tips of calcite rods provide a uniform grainy appearance to the sclerite surface." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5912771" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5912771/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="437">Fig. 17A</figureCitation>
) measuring 
<geoCoordinate box="[1028,1091,1828,1854]" degrees="0.012" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="16" pageNumber="437" precision="55" value="0.012">0.012</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate box="[1091,1168,1828,1854]" degrees="0.018" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="16" pageNumber="437" precision="55" value="-0.018">–0.018</geoCoordinate>
x 
<quantity box="[1206,1403,1827,1854]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="16" pageNumber="437" unit="mm" value="0.0175" valueMax="0.02" valueMin="0.015">
<geoCoordinate box="[1206,1268,1827,1854]" degrees="0.015" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="16" pageNumber="437" precision="55" value="0.015">0.015</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate box="[1269,1346,1827,1854]" degrees="0.020" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="16" pageNumber="437" precision="55" value="-0.02">–0.020</geoCoordinate>
mm
</quantity>
in diameter, abundant throughout the colony. A few sclerites feature surface irregularity. They are composed of calcite rods whose tips provide a granular appearance to the sclerite surface (
<figureCitation box="[930,1032,1899,1926]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1106,1130]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1082]" captionTargetId="figure-23@18.[151,1436,181,1082]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 17. Scanning electron micrographs of sclerites of Quattuoria pallida gen. nov. sp. nov. Holotype (SMNHTAU_Co_ 36071): (A) Ellipsoid platelets, a few with surface irregularity. (B) Tips of calcite rods provide a uniform grainy appearance to the sclerite surface." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5912771" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5912771/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="437">Fig. 17B</figureCitation>
). The sclerites often tend to fracture during the dehydration necessary for SEM.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1503,2034]" box="[199,960,1971,1998]" pageId="16" pageNumber="437">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,272,1971,1997]" pageId="16" pageNumber="437">Color.</emphasis>
The ethanol-preserved 
<typeStatus box="[537,635,1971,1997]" pageId="16" pageNumber="437">holotype</typeStatus>
is light cream, almost white.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1395,2007,2034]" pageId="16" pageNumber="437" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1503,2034]" box="[199,1395,2007,2034]" pageId="16" pageNumber="437">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,2008,2034]" pageId="16" pageNumber="437">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[832,918,2007,2033]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="437">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Benayahu &amp; Ekins &amp; Van Ofwegen &amp; Samimi-Namin &amp; Mcfadden" authorityYear="2022" box="[832,914,2007,2033]" class="Anthozoa" family="Xeniidae" genus="Quattuoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="16" pageNumber="437" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="pallida">pallida</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
referring to the pale color of the 
<typeStatus box="[1290,1392,2007,2033]" pageId="16" pageNumber="437">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="438" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,151,285]" pageId="17" pageNumber="438">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,151,177]" pageId="17" pageNumber="438">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Benayahu &amp; Ekins &amp; Van Ofwegen &amp; Samimi-Namin &amp; Mcfadden" authorityYear="2022" box="[323,438,151,177]" class="Anthozoa" family="Xeniidae" genus="Quattuoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="17" pageNumber="438" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="pallida">
<emphasis box="[323,438,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="438">Q. pallida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by its pinnule arrangement which lacks the organization in rows that is typical of other xeniid taxa. The ethanol-preserved 
<typeStatus box="[716,814,187,213]" pageId="17" pageNumber="438">holotype</typeStatus>
was sequenced and subsequently assigned to MOTU71. Unfortunately, no image of a live colony is available. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,258,284]" pageId="17" pageNumber="438">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[359,494,259,285]" name="Madagascar" pageId="17" pageNumber="438">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[510,575,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,944,968]" captionTargetBox="[161,1425,192,903]" captionTargetId="figure-23@4.[151,1436,179,918]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Distribution map of the material examined in the current study. Color shades on the background represent different marine realms. TA = Tropical Atlantic, TSAM = Temperate Southern America, TSA = Temperate Southern Africa, WI-P = Western Indo-Pacific, CI-P = Central Indo-Pacific, and TAA = Temperate Australasia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5912733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5912733/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="438">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
